Microfrontend App (Vite + Module Federation)
Overview

This project is a microfrontend architecture using Vite and @originjs/vite-plugin-federation, composed of:

container → host application
menu → remote module (UI)
order → remote module (cart logic)

The goal was to improve performance, modularity, and loading strategy.

Initial State (Before Refactor)
Architecture Issues
Remote modules loaded inefficiently
Incorrect module resolution (double-wrapped exports not handled)
Duplicate dynamic imports
Recursive init() call
No optimization for loading or execution order
Example (Before)
const [{ renderMenu }, { createCart }] = await Promise.all([
  import('menu/menu'),
  import('order/order'),
]);

init(); // ❌ recursive call

const [{ renderMenu }, { createCart }] = await Promise.all([
  import('menu/menu'),
  import('order/order'),
]);
Problems
❌ Duplicate imports
❌ Recursive execution
❌ No error-safe module resolution
❌ Incorrect assumption about export shape
❌ Runtime crashes (createCart is not a function)
Refactoring
Key Changes
1. Removed duplicate imports and recursion
Ensured init() runs once
Single import source of truth
2. Fixed federation module resolution

Handled Vite federation's module wrapping:

const menuModule = await import('menu/menu');
const orderModule = await import('order/order');

const renderMenu = menuModule.default.renderMenu;
const createCart = orderModule.default.createCart;
3. Improved initialization flow
async function init() {
  if (initialized) return;
  initialized = true;

  try {
    const menuModule = await import('menu/menu');
    const orderModule = await import('order/order');

    const renderMenu = menuModule.default.renderMenu;
    const createCart = orderModule.default.createCart;

    const cart = createCart();
    const menu = renderMenu(cart.add);

    // UI composition...
  } catch (err) {
    console.error('IMPORT ERROR:', err);
  }
}
After Refactor
Improvements
✅ Correct module resolution
✅ Stable async loading
✅ No redundant imports
✅ Clean initialization lifecycle
✅ Reduced runtime errors
✅ Better separation of concerns
Lighthouse Results
Metric	Before	After
Performance	80	98
Accessibility	78	96
Best Practices	100	100
SEO	82	90
What Improved Performance
1. Efficient Code Splitting
Microfrontends loaded only when needed
2. Reduced Blocking Work
Removed redundant imports and execution
3. Cleaner Execution Path
Eliminated recursive calls and duplicate logic
4. Proper Async Handling
Controlled dynamic imports
5. Federation Optimization
Correct handling of remote modules reduced runtime overhead
Lessons Learned
1. Vite Federation wraps modules

Always inspect imports:

console.log(module);
2. Match expose/import paths exactly
// expose
'./order': './src/order.js'

// import
import('order/order')
3. Avoid assumptions about exports

Always verify:

default
named exports
nested structure
Future Improvements
Standardize exports to avoid .default
Add lazy loading boundaries per route
Implement error boundaries for remotes
Add caching strategy for remoteEntry files
Use prefetch/preload for critical remotes
Running the Project
# install deps
npm install

# run remotes
npm run dev --workspace=menu
npm run dev --workspace=order

# run container
npm run dev --workspace=container
Final Notes

The main improvement came from:

Correctly handling how federation delivers modules at runtime.

This eliminated runtime errors and significantly improved performance metrics.